article.headline: Princeton 61, Holy Cross 55
article.story: PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) -- Princeton center Judson Wallace has shown the Patriot League's best he's a force to be reckoned with, and you can bet the Ivy League is taking notice. After scoring 28 to beat Colgate a week ago, Wallace scored a career-high 31 points and grabbed nine rebounds to lead Princeton to a 61-55 victory over Holy Cross Friday night. "Wallace had a spectacular game," said Holy Cross coach Ralph Willard. "We watched the Colgate film and we could see he's really turned into a heck of a player." The 6-10 junior drilled two 3-pointers from the corner to spark a 14-3 spurt that broke a 42-42 tie and derailed a Holy Cross comeback attempt. A steal by senior guard Ed Persia, who capped it with a reverse layup, pushed the lead to six. Then Wallace grabbed an offensive rebound and sank another 3 to make it 53-44 with 5:48 left. Princeton coach John Thompson was glad Wallace took command. "Let's face it, if he doesn't make those threes, we're in trouble. We needed them in a big way and he stepped up and put them in." Wallace's confidence is growing as fast as his scoring average, now at 29.5 points per game. "I feel like I can shoot as well as any center in the nation and I'm not being arrogant or anything," he said. Wallace converted 11 of his 13 shots and 3-of-5 from 3-point range. It was the most points by a Princeton player since Spencer Gloger had 34 against Alabama-Birmingham on Dec. 18, 1999. The Crusaders (2-1), the Patriot League champions the last three seasons, went on a seven-point spree to pull within four with 47 seconds left but couldn't draw closer. Princeton (2-0) closed the game with five free throws, four by Wallace, who had scored 28 in his first game against Colgate. Princeton took its biggest lead at 39-27 with 15:50 left by starting the second half with an 8-1 spurt with Wallace scoring six points. Princeton closed the first half with a 13-1 run, which ended with a spectacular steal and fallaway layup by Wallace, who was fouled with no time left. Freshman swingman Luke Owings came off the bench to score the first eight points of his career, including two 3-pointers. He finished with 11. Keith Simmons came off the bench to lead Holy Cross with 20 points and seven rebounds. After Kevin Hamilton scored to give Holy Cross its biggest lead of 25-18 with 5:06 left, Will Venable buried a 3 from the corner. After two Crusader foul shots, Owings nailed his second 3 to draw the Tigers within two. Persia drove for a layup to tie the score then Wallace hit a layup in traffic before his sensational final play.
